problem_text:
Let $p=13$, $q=31$ be primes, and $N = p^2 q = 169 \times 31 = 68,107$.

(a) Find the smallest integer $a > 1$ such that $\operatorname{ord}_{169}(a)=12$, $\operatorname{ord}_{31}(a)=3$, and $a$ is a quadratic nonresidue modulo $31$.
(b) Let $\alpha = a + \sqrt{31}$, determine the minimal polynomial of $\alpha$ over $\mathbb{Q}$, and prove or disprove the irreducibility of $f(x) = x^{12} + 5x^6 + 31$ over $\mathbb{Q}$.
(c) State:
\begin{itemize}
  \item[(i)] The exact $a$ (or an impossibility certificate if none exists);
  \item[(ii)] The minimal polynomial for $\alpha$ in standard monic form;
  \item[(iii)] Whether $f(x)$ is irreducible, with justification.
\end{itemize}
All claims must be rigorously justified and certified by explicit computational enumeration or symbolic proof.
